========== acetone init --help ==========
Create a new acetone repository

Usage: acetone init [OPTIONS] [PATH]

Arguments:
  [PATH]  Directory to create the repository in (default: --repo, or `.`)

Options:
      --object-format <OBJECT_FORMAT>  Object format (hash function) for the new repository [default: sha1] [possible values: sha1, sha256]
      --repo <REPO>                    Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument [default: .]
  -h, --help                           Print help

========== acetone status --help ==========
Show the current branch, head commit and workspace state

Usage: acetone status [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --json         Emit machine-readable JSON. The JSON shape is unstable and may change before 0.2
      --repo <REPO>  Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument [default: .]
  -h, --help         Print help

========== acetone commit --help ==========
Turn the workspace's staged changes into a commit.

Refuses when the workspace has no changes since HEAD — including, on a brand new repository, an empty root commit. There is no `--allow-empty` yet.

Usage: acetone commit [OPTIONS] --message <MESSAGE>

Options:
  -m, --message <MESSAGE>
          Commit message

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

      --trailer <TRAILER>
          A `KEY=VALUE` commit trailer; may be repeated

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone log --help ==========
Show commit history, newest first

Usage: acetone log [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --json         Emit machine-readable JSON. The JSON shape is unstable and may change before 0.2
      --repo <REPO>  Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument [default: .]
  -h, --help         Print help

