Options:
      --repo <REPO>  Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument [default: .]
  -h, --help         Print help

========== acetone merge --help ==========
Merge another version into the current branch.

Merges another version (spec §7). The workspace must be clean and a branch checked out; fast-forwards when possible, otherwise a clean three-way merge writes a two-parent merge commit. Cell-level conflicts enter a merge-in-progress state: resolve them with `acetone resolve --all-ours|--all-theirs` (or by editing the graph), then `acetone commit` to complete. Graph-level breaches (a dangling edge or a broken schema constraint) are reported and make no commit.

Usage: acetone merge [OPTIONS] <REF>

Arguments:
  <REF>
          The version to merge in (branch short name, full ref name or commit hash)

Options:
  -m, --message <MESSAGE>
          Commit message for the merge commit (default: `Merge <ref>`)

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone declare-label --help ==========
Declare a primary label's key and constraints (schema).

Declares the ordered key property names that give nodes of this label their identity. Required before Cypher `CREATE`/`MERGE` can persist nodes of the label (Invariant #3).

Usage: acetone declare-label [OPTIONS] --key <KEY> <LABEL>

Arguments:
  <LABEL>
          The primary label

Options:
      --key <KEY>
          A key property name; repeat for a composite key, in order

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

      --require <REQUIRE>
          A property that must be present (existence constraint); repeat

      --unique <UNIQUE>
          A non-key property that must be unique across nodes of this label (UNIQUE constraint); repeat

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone declare-rel-type --help ==========
Declare a relationship type (schema).

Required before Cypher can create relationships of this type under a declared schema.

Usage: acetone declare-rel-type [OPTIONS] <RTYPE>

Arguments:
  <RTYPE>
          The relationship type

Options:
      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone declare-index --help ==========
Declare a property index over `(label, properties)`.

Declares a property index `idx/<name>` (spec §3.3). The index is built from the current nodes and maintained transactionally thereafter; it accelerates equality lookups. Repeat `--property` for a **composite** index — its key is the ordered tuple of those property values. Indexes are null- and NaN-blind.

Usage: acetone declare-index [OPTIONS] --label <LABEL> --property <PROPERTY> <NAME>

Arguments:
  <NAME>
          The index name (the `idx/<name>` map)

Options:
  -l, --label <LABEL>
          The indexed primary label

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

      --property <PROPERTY>
          An indexed property; repeat, in order, for a composite index

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone reindex --help ==========
Rebuild every declared index from the nodes map.

Rebuilds every declared index (spec §3.3). A no-op when the indexes are already consistent; repairs any divergence `fsck` reports.

Usage: acetone reindex [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone schema --help ==========
Show the declared schema — labels and keys, relationship types and indexes.

Prints the repository's declared schema, grouped into labels (with their ordered key tuple and existence/unique constraints), relationship types, and property indexes. Read-only. `--at <ref>` inspects any version — a branch short name, full ref name or commit hash — without checking it out; with no `--at`, the current workspace's schema is shown.

Usage: acetone schema [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --at <AT>
          Read the schema at a specific ref (branch, tag or commit hash) instead of the current workspace state

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

      --json
          Emit machine-readable JSON. The JSON shape is unstable and may change before 0.2

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone export --help ==========
Export a graph version as per-label and per-type tables.

Exports node tables per label and edge tables per type (spec §7, §9). The inverse of `import`: exporting then importing into a fresh repo with the same schema reproduces identical map roots.

Usage: acetone export [OPTIONS] --format <FORMAT>

Options:
  -f, --format <FORMAT>
          Output format
          
          [possible values: csv, json, ndjson]

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -l, --label <LABEL>
          Export only this label's nodes

      --edge <EDGE>
          Export only this relationship type's edges

  -o, --out <OUT>
          Output file (single table) or, with neither `--label` nor `--edge`, the directory to write one table per label and type into. A single table with no `--out` goes to stdout

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone put-node --help ==========
Insert or replace a node (plumbing; single-column keys only)

Usage: acetone put-node [OPTIONS] <LABEL> <KEY>

Arguments:
  <LABEL>  Primary label
  <KEY>    Key value (parsed as an integer if it looks like one, else a string — see the CLI-level docs)

Options:
      --prop <PROP>  A `KEY=VALUE` non-key property; may be repeated
      --repo <REPO>  Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument [default: .]
  -h, --help         Print help

========== acetone rekey --help ==========
Change a node's key (single-column keys).

A key change is modelled as delete-plus-create in one commit (Invariant #3); incident edges are rewritten onto the new key. `SET` cannot change a key.

Usage: acetone rekey [OPTIONS] --message <MESSAGE> <LABEL> <OLD_KEY> <NEW_KEY>

Arguments:
  <LABEL>
          The node's primary label

  <OLD_KEY>
          The current key value

  <NEW_KEY>
          The new key value

Options:
  -m, --message <MESSAGE>
          Commit message

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone resolve --help ==========
Resolve a merge in progress by taking one whole side.

Resolves the conflicts of a merge in progress, then `commit` to complete the merge (spec §6). Cell conflicts only; graph-level violations and per-key resolution arrive later.

Usage: acetone resolve [OPTIONS]

Options:
      --all-ours
          Take the current branch's value for every conflict

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

      --all-theirs
          Take the merged-in version's value for every conflict

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone diff --help ==========
Show the graph-level difference between two versions.

Compares two versions (branch short names, full ref names or commit hashes): the nodes and relationships added (`+`), removed (`-`) or modified (`~`) from `from` to `to`.

Usage: acetone diff [OPTIONS] <FROM> <TO>

Arguments:
  <FROM>
          The base version

  <TO>
          The target version

Options:
      --json
          Emit machine-readable JSON. The JSON shape is unstable and may change before 0.2

      --repo <REPO>
          Path to the repository. Ignored by `init` when it is given its own PATH argument
          
          [default: .]

  -h, --help
          Print help (see a summary with '-h')

========== acetone get-node --help ==========
Look up a node by label and key

Usage: acetone get-node [OPTIONS] <LABEL> <KEY>

Arguments:
  <LABEL>  Primary label
  <KEY>    Key value (same parsing rule as `put-node`)

